held view, Regina Grafe argues that decentralization, not a strong and powerful Madrid, is to blame for Spain's slow march to modernity. Through a groundbreaking analysis of the market for bacalao--dried and salted codfish that was a transatlantic commodity and staple food during this period--Grafe shows how peripheral historic territories and powerful interior towns obstructed Spain's economic development through jurisdictional obstacles to trade, which exacerbated already high transport costs. She reveals how the early phases of globalization made these regions much more externally focused, and how coastal elites that were engaged in trade outside Spain sought to sustain their positions of power in relation to Madrid. Distant Tyranny offers a needed reassessment of the haphazard and regionally diverse process of state formation and market integration in early modern Spain, showing how local and regional agency paradoxically led to legitimate governance but economic backwardness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDecentralization in governmentzSpainxHistoryy17th century. 0aDecentralization in governmentzSpainxHistoryy18th century. 0aRegional disparitieszSpainxHistoryy17th century. 0aRegional disparitieszSpainxHistoryy18th century. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economic History.2bisacsh  aAtlantic trades.  aEbro.  aEurope.  aEuropean nation-states.  aEuropean state-building.  aGuadalquivir.  aHenry Swinburne.  aMadrid.  aProtestant north.  aSpain.  aSpanish economy.  aSpanish history.  aSpanish market.  aSpanish monarchy.  aabsolutism.  aaristocracy.  abacalao.  acod trade.  acommercialization.  aconsumer culture.  acontractual rule.  adecentralization.  adomestic market integration.  aeconomic development.  aeconomists.  aeighteenth-century Spain.  afa